# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: payment-request-api
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:payment-request-api/electronic-funds-transfer] The funds transfer process generally consists of a series of electronic messages sent between financial institutions directing each to make the debit and credit accounting entries necessary to complete the transaction.
[src:payment-request-api/electronic-funds-transfer] An electronic funds transfer starts when the sending customer send an electronic instruction with the purpose of making payment to the beneficiary or the receiving customer.
[src:payment-request-api/electronic-funds-transfer] EFT transactions are known by a number of names across countries and different payment systems.
[src:payment-request-api/electronic-funds-transfer] For example, in the United States, they may be referred to as "electronic checks" or "e-checks".
[src:payment-request-api/electronic-funds-transfer] In the United Kingdom, the term "BACS Payment", "bank transfer" and "bank payment" are used, in Canada, "e-Transfer" is used, while in several European countries "giro transfer" is the common term.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-request-api] This feature is not Baseline because it does not work in some of the most widely-used browsers.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-request-api] The **Payment Request API** provides a consistent user experience for merchants and users.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-request-api] It is not a new way of paying for things; instead, it's a way for users to select their preferred way of paying for things and make that information available to a merchant.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-request-api] Many problems related to online shopping cart abandonment can be traced to checkout forms, which can be difficult and time-consuming to fill out and often require multiple steps to complete.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-request-api] The **Payment Request API** is meant to reduce the steps needed to complete payment online, potentially doing away with checkout forms.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-request-api] It aims to make the checkout process more accessible by having payment apps store a user's details, which are passed along to a merchant, hopefully without requiring an HTML form.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-request-api] To request a payment, a web page creates a `PaymentRequest` object in response to a user action that initiates a payment, such as clicking a "Purchase" button.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-request-api] The `PaymentRequest` allows the web page to exchange information with the user agent while the user provides input to complete the transaction.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-request-api] You can find a complete guide in Using the Payment Request API.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-request-api] An object that contains address information; used for billing and shipping addresses, for example.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-request-api] An object that provides the API for creating and managing the user agent's payment interface.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-request-api] Enables the web page to update the details of the payment request in response to a user action.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-request-api] Represents the user changing payment instrument (e.g., switching from one payment method to another).
[src:payment-request-api/payment-request-api] An object returned after the user selects a payment method and approves a payment request.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-request-api] Represents the browser requiring the merchant (website) to validate themselves as allowed to use a particular payment handler (e.g., registered as allowed to use Apple Pay).
[src:payment-request-api/payment-service-provider] A **payment service provider** (**PSP**) is a third-party company that allows businesses to accept electronic payments, such as credit card and debit card payments.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-service-provider] PSPs act as intermediaries between those who make payments, i.e. consumers, and those who accept them, i.e. retailers.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-service-provider] They will often provide merchant services and act as a payment gateway or payment processor for e-commerce and brick and mortar businesses.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-service-provider] They may also offer risk management services for card and bank based payments, transaction payment matching, digital wallets, reporting, fund remittance, currency exchange and fraud protection.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-service-provider] The PSP will typically provide software to integrate with e-commerce websites or point of sale systems.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-service-provider] PSPs establish technical connections with acquiring banks and card networks, enabling merchants to accept different payment methods without the need to partner with a particular bank.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-service-provider] They fully manage payment processing and external network relationships, making the merchant less dependent on banking institutions.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-service-provider] PSP can also offer risk management services for card and bank based payments, transaction payment matching, reporting, fund remittance and fraud protection.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-service-provider] Some PSPs provide services to process other next generation methods (payment systems) including cash payments, wallets, prepaid cards or vouchers, and even paper or e-check processing.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-service-provider] PSP fees are typically charged in one of two ways: as a percentage of each transaction, or as a fixed cost per transaction.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-service-provider] European payment service providers are supervised based on the European Payment Services Directive.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-service-provider] Each merchant remains responsible for his own actions and must accordingly ensure that the selected provider observes the guidelines, e.g. with regard to data protection.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-service-provider] Compliance with PCI DSS guidelines is important.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-service-provider] There are four levels of PCI compliance, that must be respected by the PSP.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-service-provider] Depending on the volume of transactions as well as other details about the level of risk assessed by payment brands, the payment service provider has to follow higher standards.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-service-provider] As of 2022, there were more than 900 payment providers in the world.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-service-provider] More than 300 offer services just for Europe and North America.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-service-provider] The global payment service provider market is expected to reach $US88 billion by 2027 from $US40 billion in 2019.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-service-provider] In 2010, the People's Bank of China issued administrative measures regarding online non-financial payment services.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-service-provider] These measures retroactively recognized the legal status of online third-party payment platforms like Alipay.
[src:payment-request-api/payment-service-provider] Prior to the 2010 measures, these services existed in a legal grey area.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] The **`PaymentRequest`** interface's **`show()`** method instructs the user agent to begin the process of showing and handling the user interface for the payment request to the user.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] Only one payment request can be in the process of being handled at once, across all documents.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] If your architecture doesn't necessarily have all of the data ready to go at the moment it instantiates the payment interface by calling `show()`, specify the `detailsPromise` parameter, providing a `Promise` that is fulfilled once the data is ready.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] If this is provided, `show()` will not allow the user to interact with the payment interface until the promise is fulfilled, so that data can be updated prior to the user engaging with the payment process.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] Processing the result and, if necessary, calling `PaymentResponse.retry()` to retry a failed payment can all be done either asynchronously or synchronously, depending on your needs.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] For the best user experience, asynchronous solutions are typically the best way to go.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] Most examples on MDN and elsewhere use `async`/`await` to wait asynchronously while results are validated and so forth.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] Either an object or a `Promise` that resolves to an object.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] Provide this if your architecture requires that the payment request's details need to be updated between instantiating the payment interface and the user beginning to interact with it.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] An array of objects, each describing one line item for the payment request.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] An object describing the monetary value of the item.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] A string containing a valid 3-letter ISO 4217 currency identifier (ISO 4217) indicating the currency used for the payment `value`.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] A string containing a valid decimal value representing the mount of currency constituting the payment amount.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] This string must only contain an optional leading "-" to indicate a negative value, then one or more digits from 0 to 9, and an optional decimal point (".", regardless of locale) followed by at least one more digit.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] A string specifying a human-readable name or description of the item or service being charged for.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] This may be displayed to the user by the user agent, depending on the design of the interface.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] A Boolean value which is `true` if the specified `amount` has not yet been finalized.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] This can be used to show items such as shipping or tax amounts that depend upon the selection of shipping address, shipping option, or so forth.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] The user agent may show this information but is not required to do so.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] A string specifying an error message to present to the user.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] When calling `updateWith()`, including `error` in the updated data causes the user agent to display the text as a general error message.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] For address-field specific errors, use the `shippingAddressErrors` field.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] A string that represents the payment method identifier.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] The payment method identifier only applies if the user selects this payment method.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] An object that overrides the `total` property of the `detailsPromise` parameter if this payment method is selected by the user.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] The property takes the same input with the `total` property of the `detailsPromise` parameter.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] An `Array` of objects provide additional display items that are appended to the `displayItems` property of the `detailsPromise` parameter if this payment method is selected by the user.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] This property is commonly used to add a discount or surcharge line item indicating the reason for the different total amount for the selected payment method that the user agent may display.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] The property takes the same input with the `displayItems` property of the `detailsPromise` parameter.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] A serializable object that provides optional information that might be needed by the supported payment methods.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] For example, you can use one to adjust the total payment amount based on the selected payment method ("5% cash discount!").
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] An object which includes an error message for each property of the shipping address that could not be validated.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] An array of objects, each describing one available shipping option from which the user may choose.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] An object with the same properties as the objects in `displayItems` providing an updated total for the payment.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] Make sure this equals the sum of all of the items in `displayItems`.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] You must update this value yourself anytime the total amount due changes.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] This lets you have flexibility for how to handle things like tax, discounts, and other adjustments to the total price charged.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] A `Promise` that eventually resolves with a `PaymentResponse`.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] The promise is resolved when the user accepts the payment request (such as by clicking a "Pay" button in the browser's payment sheet).
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] Exceptions are not thrown but returned when the `Promise` rejects.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] Returned if the user agent is already showing a payment panel.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] Only one payment panel may be visible at a time *across all documents loaded by the user agent*.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] The promise is also rejected with `AbortError` if the user cancels the payment request.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] Returned if the same payment has already been shown for this request (its state is `interactive` because it is being shown already).
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] Returned if the user agent does not support the payment methods specified when the `PaymentRequest` constructor was called.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] Returned if the call to `show()` was not in response to a user action, such as a `click` or `keyup` event.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] Other reasons a `SecurityError` may be thrown are at the discretion of the user agent, and may include situations such as too many calls to `show()` being made in a short time or `show()` being called while payment requests are blocked by parental controls.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] The user has to interact with the page or a UI element in order for this feature to work.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] The most common patterns for using `show()` involve either the `async`/`await` syntax or the use of `show().then().catch()` to handle the response and any possible rejection.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] Here, a custom function called `checkAllValues()` looks at each value in the `response` and ensures that they're valid, returning `true` if every field is valid or `false` if any are not.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] If and only if every field is valid, the `complete()` method is called on the response with the string `"success"`, which indicates that everything is valid and that the payment can complete accordingly.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] If any fields have unacceptable values, or if an exception is thrown by the previous code, `complete()` is called with the string `"fail"`, which indicates that the payment process is complete and failed.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] Instead of immediately failing, you could choose to call `retry()` on the response object to ask the user agent to try to process the payment again; this should usually only be done after the user has made any needed corrections to the order.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] Starting the payment process, in the end, is as simple as calling the `processPayment()` method.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] This is functionally equivalent to the `processPayment()` method using the `await` syntax.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] See the article Using promises for more information if you need more information about working with promises.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] In the following example, a `PaymentRequest` object is instantiated before the `show()` method is called.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] This method triggers the user agent's built-in process for retrieving payment information from the user.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] The `show()` method returns a `Promise` that resolves to a `PaymentResponse` object when the user interaction is complete.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] The developer then uses the information in the `PaymentResponse` object to format and send payment data to the server.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] You should send the payment information to the server asynchronously so that the final call to `paymentResponse.complete()` can indicate the success or failure of the payment.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest-show] The following example shows how to update the payment sheet as it's being presented to the end-user.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest] The Payment Request API's **`PaymentRequest`** interface is the primary access point into the API, and lets web content and apps accept payments from the end user on behalf of the operator of the site or the publisher of the app.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest] A unique identifier for a particular `PaymentRequest`, which can be set via `details.id`.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest] When none is set, it defaults to a UUID.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest] If requested via payment options, returns the shipping address chosen by the user for the purposes of calculating shipping.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest] This property is only populated if the constructor is called with the `requestShipping` flag set to true.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest] Additionally, in some browsers, the parts of the address will be redacted for privacy until the user indicates they are ready to complete the transaction (i.e., they hit "Pay").
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest] Returns the identifier of the selected shipping option.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest] Returns the type of shipping used to fulfill the transaction.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest] This will be one of `shipping`, `delivery`, `pickup`, or `null` if a value was not provided in the constructor.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest] Indicates whether the Secure payment confirmation feature is available.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest] Indicates whether the `PaymentRequest` object can make a payment before calling `show()`.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest] Causes the user agent to begin the user interaction for the payment request.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest] Causes the user agent to end the payment request and to remove any user interface that might be shown.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest] With some payment handlers (e.g., Apple Pay), this event handler is called to handle the `merchantvalidation` event, which is dispatched when the user agent requires that the merchant validate that the merchant or vendor requesting payment is legitimate.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest] With some payment handlers (e.g., Apple Pay), dispatched whenever the user changes payment instrument, like switching from a credit card to a debit card.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest] Dispatched whenever the user changes their shipping address.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentrequest] Dispatched whenever the user changes a shipping option.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentresponse] The **`PaymentResponse`** interface of the Payment Request API is returned after a user selects a payment method and approves a payment request.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentresponse] Returns a JSON-serializable object that provides a payment method specific message used by the merchant to process the transaction and determine successful fund transfer.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentresponse] The contents of the object depend on the payment method being used.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentresponse] Developers need to consult whomever controls the URL for the expected shape of the details object.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentresponse] Returns the payment method identifier for the payment method that the user selected, for example, Visa, Mastercard, PayPal, etc.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentresponse] Returns the email address supplied by the user.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentresponse] This option is only present when the `requestPayerEmail` option is set to `true` in the `options` parameter of the `PaymentRequest()` constructor.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentresponse] This option is only present when the `requestPayerName` option is set to true in the `options` parameter of the `PaymentRequest()` constructor.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentresponse] Returns the phone number supplied by the user.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentresponse] This option is only present when the `requestPayerPhone` option is set to `true` in the `options` parameter of the `PaymentRequest()` constructor.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentresponse] Returns the identifier of the `PaymentRequest` that produced the current response.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentresponse] This is the same value supplied in the `PaymentRequest()` constructor by `details.id`.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentresponse] Returns the shipping Address supplied by the user.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentresponse] This option is only present when the `requestShipping` option is set to `true` in the `options` parameter of the `PaymentRequest()` constructor.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentresponse] Returns the ID attribute of the shipping option selected by the user.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentresponse] If something is wrong with the payment response's data (and there is a recoverable error), this method allows a merchant to request that the user retry the payment.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentresponse] The method takes an object as argument, which is used to signal to the user exactly what is wrong with the payment response so they can try to correct any issues.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentresponse] Notifies the user agent that the user interaction is over.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentresponse] This causes any remaining user interface to be closed.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentresponse] This method should only be called after the Promise returned by the `PaymentRequest.show()` method.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentresponse] Returns a JSON object representing this `PaymentResponse` object.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentresponse] Listen to this event using `addEventListener()` or by assigning an event listener to the `oneventname` property of this interface.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentresponse] Fired during a retry when the user makes changes to their personal information while filling out a payment request form.
[src:payment-request-api/paymentresponse] Allows the developer to revalidate any requested user data (e.g., the phone number or the email address) if it changes.
[src:payment-request-api/using-the-payment-request-api] The Payment Request API provides a browser-based method of connecting users and their preferred payment systems and platforms to merchants that they want to pay for goods and services.
[src:payment-request-api/using-the-payment-request-api] This article is a guide to making use of the Payment Request API, with examples and suggested best practices.
[src:payment-request-api/using-the-payment-request-api] This section details the basics of using the Payment Request API to make a payment.
[src:payment-request-api/using-the-payment-request-api] A payment request always starts with the creation of a new `PaymentRequest` object — using the `PaymentRequest()` constructor.
[src:payment-request-api/using-the-payment-request-api] Once the `PaymentRequest` object has been created, you call the `PaymentRequest.show()` method on it to initiate the payment request.
[src:payment-request-api/using-the-payment-request-api] This object provides the developer with access to details they can use to complete the logical steps required after the payment completes, such as an email address to contact the customer, a shipping address for mailing goods out to them, etc.
[src:payment-request-api/using-the-payment-request-api] In the code above, you'll see that we've called the `PaymentResponse.complete()` method to signal that the interaction has finished — you'd use this to carry out finishing steps, like updating the user interface to tell the user the transaction is complete, etc.
[src:payment-request-api/using-the-payment-request-api] There are some other useful payment request methods worth knowing about.
[src:payment-request-api/using-the-payment-request-api] `PaymentRequest.canMakePayment()` can be used to check whether the `PaymentRequest` object is capable of making a payment before you start the payment process.
[src:payment-request-api/using-the-payment-request-api] `PaymentRequest.abort()` can be used to abort the payment request if required.
[src:payment-request-api/using-the-payment-request-api] You can effectively detect support for the Payment Request API by checking if the user's browser supports `PaymentRequest`, i.e., `if (window.PaymentRequest)`.
[src:payment-request-api/using-the-payment-request-api] In the following snippet, a merchant page performs this check, and if it returns `true` updates the checkout button to use `PaymentRequest` instead of legacy web forms.
[src:payment-request-api/using-the-payment-request-api] Checking whether users can make payments is always useful.
[src:payment-request-api/using-the-payment-request-api] One useful technique to employ is customizing the payment request button depending on whether users can make payments.
[src:payment-request-api/using-the-payment-request-api] In the following snippet we do just this — depending on whether the user can make a fast payment or needs to add payment credentials first, the title of the checkout button changes between "Fast Checkout with W3C" and "Setup W3C Checkout".
[src:payment-request-api/using-the-payment-request-api] In both cases, the checkout button calls `PaymentRequest.show()`.
[src:payment-request-api/using-the-payment-request-api] If the checkout flow needs to know whether `PaymentRequest.canMakePayment()` will return `true` even before all line items and their prices are known, you can instantiate `PaymentRequest` with dummy data and pre-query `.canMakePayment()`.
[src:payment-request-api/using-the-payment-request-api] If you call `.canMakePayment()` multiple times, keep in mind that the first parameter to the `PaymentRequest` constructor should contain the same method names and data.
[src:payment-request-api/using-the-payment-request-api] If you select to pay with the BobBucks demo payment provider on this merchant page, it tries to call `PaymentRequest.show()`, while intercepting the `NotSupportedError` `DOMException`.
[src:payment-request-api/using-the-payment-request-api] If this payment method is not supported, it redirects to the signup page for BobBucks.
[src:payment-request-api/using-the-payment-request-api] If the merchant desires to collect additional information not part of the API (e.g., additional delivery instructions), the merchant can show a page with additional `<input type="text">` fields after the checkout.
[src:payment-request-api/using-the-payment-request-api] Some use cases (e.g., paying for fuel at a service station) involve pre-authorizing payment.
[src:payment-request-api/using-the-payment-request-api] One way to do this is through a Web-based Payment Handler (see the Web-based Payment Handler API).
[src:payment-request-api/using-the-payment-request-api] At the time of writing, that specification includes a `canmakepayment` event that a Web-based Payment Handler could make use of to return authorization status.
[src:payment-request-api/using-the-payment-request-api] This payment handler would need to live in a service worker at `https://example.com/preauth` scope.
